natural problem: If $f(x) = \frac{3x-2}{x-2}$, what is the value of $f(-2) +f(-1)+f(0)$? Express your answer as a common fraction.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. x \<noteq> 2 \<longrightarrow> f x = (3 * x - 2) / (x - 2)"
shows  "f (-2) + f (-1) + f 0 = 14 / 3"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 If $f(x) = \frac{3x-2}{x-2}$, what is the value of $f(-2) +f(-1)+f(0)$? Express your answer as a common fraction. The final Answer is \frac{14}{3}
 ### Proof
 $f(-2)+f(-1)+f(0)=\frac{3(-2)-2}{-2-2}+\frac{3(-1)-2}{-1-2}+\frac{3(0)-2}{0-2}=\frac{-8}{-4}+\frac{-5}{-3}+\frac{-2}{-2}=2+\frac{5}{3}+1=\boxed{\frac{14}{3}}$
 *)

theorem
fixes x f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. x \<noteq> 2 \<longrightarrow> f x = (3 * x - 2) / (x - 2)"
shows  "f (-2) + f (-1) + f 0 = 14 / 3"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
